X-ray photoelectron spectroscopy (XPS) measurements were used to examine the elemental composition and chemical structure of GO, rGO and N-GQDs/rGOs samples (Fig. 2
                        ). As presented in Fig. 2a, the survey spectra of all samples display pronounced C1s and O1s peaks at around 284.6 and 532.5 eV. After the hydrothermal reaction, the relative intensity of the C1s peak increased, while the relative intensity of the O1s peak diminished from GO to rGO and N-GQDs/rGOs, suggesting the incomplete reduction of GO (Table 2

                        ). Moreover, a sensible N1s peak at around 400 eV can be found in N-GQDs/rGOs samples, which illustrate that the samples have been doped with nitrogen. Fig. 2b-d shows the high-resolution O1s XPS spectra of GO, rGO and N-GQDs/rGO-20 samples. The O1s peaks of these samples can be deconvoluted into five sub-peaks centered at around 530.7, 531.6, 532.2, 532.6 and 533.5 eV that correspond to characteristic peaks of quinone O, carboxyl group, carbonyl group, epoxy group and hydroxyl group, respectively [34]. In addition, the content of epoxy groups, which are harmful to the electrochemical property of carbon materials, is greatly reduced from GO to rGO and N-GQDs/rGO-20, while the content of carboxyl and hydroxyl groups is relatively increased. These remaining oxygen-containing functional groups can enhance the hydrophilicity of the material and improve its pseudocapacitance [35] (see Table 3).
